Now that I am happy with how quality is looking lets see what it looks like

No scores of less than 3. Scores of 3 and 4 are uncommon. 5 or better represents the bulk of the wines. After seeing the distribution of quality I wanted to check the mean and standard deviation. It was a little tricky after converting quality to a factor.

qual_mean <- mean(as.numeric(levels(wine_quality$quality)[wine_quality$quality]))
qual_sd <- sd(as.numeric(levels(wine_quality$quality)[wine_quality$quality]))
qual_mean
## [1] 5.636023
qual_sd
## [1] 0.8075694

The mean and standard deviation look appropriate for this distribution

Now lets look at some of the other variables that could contribute to the quality rating

Lets see what the variables related to acidity look like.

For single variable analysis I prefer the density plot since you dont have to be overly concerned tweaking the binwidth.

There could be a bimodal distribution happening here with volatile.acidity.

Now for citric.acid

Several wines have 0.00 g/L citric acid. The density plot is a is a little hard to tell where the bulk of these data are. The histogram doesnt really help the situation. citric.acid distribution has elements of a uniform distribution. There is an interesting spike of wines with 0.24 and 0.49 g/L citric acid. I wonder if these could additional modes could indicate wine from a specific producer.

This plot sheds a bit of light on where the majority of the citric.acid observations are. Looks like about half of the observations are between 0.1 and 0.4 g.

Lets take a look at pH

Most wines in this data set fall between 3.1 and 3.5

Now lets see what the variables for sulphate and related compounds content looks like

All of the sulphate variables seem to have a similar right skew. There seem to be some wines with very high sulphate content relative to the rest of the wines.

Finally lets see what alcohol and related parameters looks like:

Most wines have between 9% and 11% ABV

Half of the observations are between 9.5% to 11.1% ABV

No surprises here.

There are some wines with very high residual sugars; lets zoom in on the mean:

## Warning: Removed 48 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Seems like most of the values are between 1.5 and 2.5. There seems to be areas of increased frequency at 4 and 5 out on the tail.

## Warning: Removed 1388 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

There seemed to be some secondary modes in the original plot, however I think all I was noticing places where there sparse values making it seem like an additional peak.

Box plot confirms what I was seeing in the density plot - most of the falling in a narrow lower band around the median with some widely spaced outliers.

Looks like most of the red wine sampled fell in the 9% to 11% ABV range. Alcohol volumes of 9.5% and 10.9% seem to more common. The plot of the density variable looks almost too perfectly normally distributed. It does make sense since there arent many wines with a very high alcohol content or very high residual sugars. I was expecting the alcohol and residual sugar plots to appear very similar. The relationship between these two variables must be more complex than I expected.

Last but not least - chlorides. This physiochemical measurement didnt fall in to any of the other logical groupings so it has been plotted on its own.

Very high right skew here. Very few observations outside of the 0.05 to 0.15 range.

There are 1599 red wines in this data set each with measurements of 11 of their physio-chemical properties and a sensory measurement of quality. The quality variable is the median of at least 3 taste tests by wine experts. I have chosen to make quality and ordered factor to reflect the specification the researchers used when collecting these data - the higher the number, the better the wine.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The data set has several related groups of variables. With a view to predicting a quality rating one might consider the primary flavor or aromatic factors such as acidity (fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid) or sweetness (residual.sugars). The data set provides other measurements of interest. I am particularly interested in discovering if the group of variables for amounts of sulfur containing compounds (free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, sulphates) has any effect on the quality score.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I suspect that there might be multicolinearity in this data since often times the presence of higher acidity or sugars can alter ones perception of other compounds. I plan to investigate the how acidity and higher sugar content work in conjunction with the sulfur containing compound to effect the quality rating.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Most of the variables in this data set seemed to be valuable on their own and there wasnt any clear way to combine any of them in a meaningful way. One alteration I did make was to convert the quality variable in to a factor for easier analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Some of the distributions were unexpected but not bizarre in any way.

Seeing this correllation plot I am curious if the taste testers were aware of the wines alcohol content during tasting. If so, I would be concerned that this is a source of bias in these data. The alcohol variable seems to explain about substantial amount of the variance in the quality variable. volatile.acidity has fairly high negative correllation to the quality variable. Not surprised about that. Aceitic acid vapor is not what most people are looking for when they take the first sip. I am curious about the slightly elevated correllation of sulphates and the quality variable. Despite being evident during the univariate exploration, I am still a little surprised by the 0 values for residual.sugar for alcohol and quality.

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = quality, y = alcohol)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 1/10)

Tried several alpha values and jitter. There seems to be a lower mean when quality is 5 but a scatter plot with a factor makes things a little unclear. Probably better as box plot I am thinking.

# http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3989987/joining-means-on-a-boxplot-with-a-line-ggplot2
ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = quality, y = alcohol)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  # aes(group = 1) added to line plot forces stat_summary to be scoped to pre-aggregated data so line can connect means from each group
  stat_summary(aes(group = 1), fun.y = mean, geom = "line", show.legend = FALSE) +
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "point", shape = "", size = 2, show.legend = FALSE)

Thats better. With the box plot you can the trend from the scatter plot more clearly. Most of the lower scores tend to have an alcohol content around 10. Scores of 5 are densly packed around the median with several outliers, some of which are extreme. Starting with scores of 6 and above there seems to be an upward trend in the mean alcohol content. To keep this in prespective I want to remind myself how many observations fall in to each of the scores. Adding the mean marker m and a connecting line makes the tendancy in these data clearer.

summary(wine_quality$quality)
##   3   4   5   6   7   8 
##  10  53 681 638 199  18

Seeing that this trend presentes itself over more than half of the observations is some additional supporting evidence to the correlation score alcohol and quality have.

Now for the next variable that has a higher correlation to quality, volatile.acidity

# http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3989987/joining-means-on-a-boxplot-with-a-line-ggplot2
ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = quality, y = volatile.acidity)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  # aes(group = 1) added to line plot forces stat_summary to be scoped to pre-aggregated data so line can connect means from each group
  stat_summary(aes(group = 1), fun.y = mean, geom = "line", show.legend = FALSE) +
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "point", shape = "", size = 2, show.legend = FALSE)

We can see the the negative correllation clearly here. The IQR is compressing as the quality improves. There is an overall negative trend in volatile.acidity as the quality increases.

The next interesting correllation from the inital corellation plot I want to examine is sulphates by chlorides.

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = sulphates, y = chlorides)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/15)

For the majority of the wines sampled the amount of chlorides is fairly consistent except of a few moderate and extreme cases. Sames goes for sulphates except for having the bulk of the values over a slightly larger range. There are observations where the suphate measurement is high and the corresponding chloride measurement is low or high. There are no observations where the suphate measurement is low and the chloride measurement is exteme.

There seems to be a fairly strong relationship between volatile.acidity and citric.acid.

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = citric.acid, y = volatile.acidity)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10)

There is a wide range of volatile.acidity values for each citric.acid measurement. There does seems to be a negative correllation here but the variance would be quite high. The bands of common citric.acid measurements (0.0, 0.24, and 0.49) that were noted during the univariate exploration are visible here. Visually, it seems that beyond citric.acid measurements of 0.49 the trend reverses and begins upward.

Superimposing a linear model confirms the tendancy is approaching flat but still slightly negative.

The fixed.acidity and citric.acid measurements appear to have a very strong correllation. I was going to ignore this relationship until I read the description of each of the variables again. I was under the impression that the fixed.acidity measurement was a measurement of all acidity except aecetic acid. Since this is not the case lets investigate this relationship.

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = citric.acid, y = fixed.acidity)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10)

Visually there seems to be a slight exponential curve. Lets see what log(fixed.acidity) looks like.

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = citric.acid, y = fixed.acidity)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10) +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm")

ggplot(wine_quality, aes(x = citric.acid, y = log(fixed.acidity))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10) +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm")

With the linear model overlayed over the original plot the cure is no longer perceptable.
